---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const inbox = "thetourist1@proton.me";
const privateSubject = encodeURIComponent("Private information for verification");
const privateBody = encodeURIComponent(`Information:\n\n\nSources, if any:\n- \n\nNote: normal email is not anonymous by itself. If the risk is high, read the safety page before sending material.\n`);
const privateUrl = `mailto:${inbox}?subject=${privateSubject}&body=${privateBody}`;
const torSearchUrl = "https://www.google.com/search?q=Tor+Browser+download";
const torPracticeSearchUrl = "https://www.google.com/search?q=Tor+Browser+security+practices";
const protonSearchUrl = "https://www.google.com/search?q=Proton+Mail+sign+up";
---

<BaseLayout lang="en" title="Source safety | 50 Shades of Power" description="How to send information with more care, without fake anonymity promises.">
  <section class="section narrow">
    <p class="eyebrow">Source safety</p>
    <h1>Before you send information.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Email and normal forms are not anonymous by themselves. This page gives practical steps to reduce
      risk, but it does not promise perfect anonymity.
    </p>

    <div class="guide-stack">
      <article>
        <h2>For low-risk material</h2>
        <p>
          You can email the archive with links, public documents, dates and a short explanation.
          If you do not want to use your personal address, use Proton, SimpleLogin or another alias.
        </p>
        <a class="button primary" href={privateUrl}>Send private information</a>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>For sensitive material</h2>
        <p>
          Do not use work email, personal email, social accounts or devices that are easy to link to you.
          Search for Tor Browser yourself and check that the result is an official domain before downloading.
          Do not log into personal accounts, and do not include your name, phone or identifying details in the text.
        </p>
        <a class="button secondary" href={torSearchUrl} rel="noreferrer">Search Tor Browser</a>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>Create a separate inbox</h2>
        <p>
          For more sensitive information, create a new Proton address or alias only for this work,
          inside Tor Browser. Do not use a recovery email, phone number, name, known pseudonym or password
          that links back to you. If the service asks for verification with personal details, that can create
          a link. Do not later open that inbox from a normal browser or personal device.
        </p>
        <a class="button secondary" href={protonSearchUrl} rel="noreferrer">Search Proton Mail</a>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>Documents can identify you</h2>
        <p>
          PDF, Word, photos and other files can contain metadata: author, device, location, creation time
          or edit history. Before sending sensitive material, remove metadata or send public links when possible.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>What to avoid</h2>
        <p>
          Do not send from a work network, do not mention yourself in the text, do not use a pseudonym
          that you use elsewhere, and do not open documents downloaded through Tor while online. Tor Project
          warns that documents can load resources outside Tor and reveal your IP address.
        </p>
        <a class="button secondary" href={torPracticeSearchUrl} rel="noreferrer">Tor practices</a>
      </article>

      <article>
        <h2>What happens after you send</h2>
        <p>
          Nothing is published automatically. Information is used for verification, compared with public
          sources and may appear only after identifying details are removed and there is documentary basis.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
